    <header>
        <h1>Games Rules</h1>
    </header>

    <main>
        <section>
            <h2>General Conduct</h2>
            <p><strong>Fair Play:</strong> All players are expected to conduct themselves in a sportsmanlike manner. Respect for opponents, officials, and spectators is paramount.</p>
            <p><strong>Safety First:</strong> Players must use appropriate safety gear and be aware of their surroundings to prevent injuries.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Equipment</h2>
            <p><strong>Proper Gear:</strong> Players must use equipment specific to each sport, such as appropriate racquets and balls.</p>
            <p><strong>Equipment Tampering:</strong> Modifying equipment in a manner that gives an unfair advantage is strictly prohibited.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Starting the Game</h2>
            <p><strong>Coin Toss:</strong> Matches typically begin with a coin toss to decide who serves first.</p>
            <p><strong>Side Switch:</strong> Players switch sides at the end of a set or game, following the rules of the specific sport.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Scoring</h2>
            <p><strong>Point System:</strong> Points are scored as per the standard rules of each sport.</p>
            <p><strong>Honesty in Scoring:</strong> Players are responsible for keeping track of and honestly reporting the score throughout the game.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Serving</h2>
            <p><strong>Service Rules:</strong> Each game starts with a service, which should be executed according to the specific sport’s rules.</p>
            <p><strong>Service Faults:</strong> Faults in service are handled according to the individual game’s regulations.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Ball Out of Play</h2>
            <p><strong>Boundary Rules:</strong> If the ball goes out of the court boundaries, the opposing player or team scores a point.</p>
            <p><strong>Wall Interactions:</strong> In squash and padel, a ball that hits the surrounding walls in certain ways may be considered out of play.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Interferences</h2>
            <p><strong>Avoiding Obstructions:</strong> Players must not intentionally obstruct their opponent’s play.</p>
            <p><strong>Replaying Points:</strong> In case of unintentional interference, the point is typically replayed.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Game Interruptions</h2>
            <p><strong>Injury or Distraction:</strong> Play can be paused in case of injury or accidental interruption. If a player cannot continue, the opponent wins by default.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Match Conclusion</h2>
            <p><strong>Winning the Match:</strong> A match is won when a player or team reaches the required number of games or sets.</p>
            <p><strong>Post-Match Conduct:</strong> Players should acknowledge each other respectfully at the end of the match.</p>
        </section>

        <section>
            <h2>Respect and Sportsmanship</h2>
            <p><strong>Upholding Integrity:</strong> Respect and integrity should be maintained at all times, both on and off the court.</p>
            <p><strong>Resolving Disputes:</strong> Any disputes should be resolved amicably or through a designated official.</p>
        </section>
    </main>
